// agnosia_phi.hexa — P105 Agnosia Φ (perception without recognition)
//
// Roadmap: shared/roadmaps/anima.json P105
//   "Agnosia — percept forms but recognition fails. Lissauer 1890
//    apperceptive vs associative dissociation."
//
// ─── Clinical / philosophical frame ──────────────────────────────
//
// Lissauer (1890) first distinguished two stages in object recognition:
//   1. APPERCEPTION — forming a coherent percept from sensory fragments.
//   2. ASSOCIATION  — matching the percept to stored semantic knowledge.
//
// Normal object recognition is a three-link chain:
//   raw sensory → PERCEPT (coherent shape) → SEMANTIC (meaning/category)
//                                           → NAMING (lexical label)
// Damage at different points yields qualitatively distinct syndromes:
//
// Apperceptive agnosia (Milner 1991; Farah 2004):
//   Cannot form coherent percepts. Cannot copy a drawing. Cannot match
//   objects across viewpoints. Early visual processing (V1/V2/V4) is
//   damaged. The percept link breaks, and downstream semantic and naming
//   NECESSARILY fail because there is nothing to associate.
//
// Associative agnosia (Rubens & Benson 1971; Farah 2004):
//   Percept is INTACT — patient can copy a drawing with exquisite detail.
//   But they cannot say WHAT it is. The semantic link from percept to
//   stored object knowledge is severed. Naming fails downstream because
//   semantics is the route to naming.
//
// Prosopagnosia (Bodamer 1947; De Renzi 1986; Duchaine & Nakayama 2006):
//   Face-specific recognition failure. Object recognition is intact (can
//   name a cup, a key, a car). Face recognition impaired (cannot identify
//   familiar faces — own face in mirror may be unrecognized). Face
//   processing recruits FFA (fusiform face area), a specialized pathway
//   that can be selectively damaged leaving general object recognition
//   through LOC (lateral occipital complex) intact.
//
// Modality specificity (Beauvois 1982; Riddoch & Humphreys 1987):
//   Visual agnosia can be modality-specific: patient cannot recognize
//   an object BY SIGHT but immediately recognizes it BY TOUCH (tactile
//   pathway intact). Same object, same semantic store, different sensory
//   route. This proves that the deficit is in the visual-to-semantic
//   mapping, not in the semantic store itself.
//
// ─── Model architecture ──────────────────────────────────────────
//
// We model the recognition chain as four measurable channels:
//
//   SENSORY  → raw input features (edge, orientation, texture fragments)
//   PERCEPT  → bound coherent representation (integrated shape)
//   SEMANTIC → category / meaning activation
//   NAMING   → lexical label activation
//
// Each channel is a time-series trace. Normal recognition means all
// channels are coupled: sensory drives percept, percept drives semantic,
// semantic drives naming. Φ_recognition is measured as MI across the
// chain.
//
// Agnosia modes:
//   NORMAL        — all couplings strong; full chain percept→semantic→naming
//   APPERCEPTIVE  — sensory→percept coupling broken (gain_percept → 0)
//                   downstream semantic and naming necessarily collapse
//   ASSOCIATIVE   — percept intact, percept→semantic coupling broken
//                   (gain_semantic → 0); naming collapses downstream
//   PROSOPAGNOSIA — object chain intact, face-specific chain impaired
//                   (face_gain → 0, object_gain → 1.0)
//
// Face vs object pathways:
//   We model two parallel recognition chains sharing the same architecture:
//     OBJECT chain — LOC pathway, gain = object_gain (default 1.0)
//     FACE chain   — FFA pathway, gain = face_gain   (default 1.0)
//   Prosopagnosia selectively impairs face_gain while preserving object_gain.
//
// Modality specificity:
//   We model two sensory modalities feeding the SAME semantic store:
//     VISUAL  pathway — gain = visual_gain (default 1.0)
//     TACTILE pathway — gain = tactile_gain (default 1.0)
//   Visual agnosia sets visual_gain → 0 but tactile_gain stays at 1.0.
//   The patient recognizes the object by touch, not sight.
//
// ─── Φ measurements ──────────────────────────────────────────────
//
//   Φ_percept   = MI(sensory, percept)    — perceptual binding
//   Φ_semantic  = MI(percept, semantic)   — meaning extraction
//   Φ_naming    = MI(semantic, naming)    — lexical access
//   Φ_recognition = Φ_percept × Φ_semantic × Φ_naming (product form:
//                   any break collapses the whole chain)
//
// ─── 5 self-tests (5/5 gate) ────────────────────────────────────
//
// T1 Normal recognition:
//   Φ_percept, Φ_semantic, Φ_naming all > AG_PHI_MIN.
//   Φ_recognition (product) > AG_RECOG_MIN.
//   The full chain is operational.
//
// T2 Apperceptive agnosia:
//   Percept gain collapsed → Φ_percept drops.
//   Downstream Φ_semantic and Φ_naming also collapse (no percept to
//   associate or name). Φ_recognition ≈ 0.
//
// T3 Associative agnosia:
//   Percept intact (Φ_percept preserved within AG_PRESERVE_TOL).
//   Semantic coupling broken → Φ_semantic drops.
//   Naming fails downstream. But Φ_percept is spared — patient CAN
//   copy the drawing.
//
// T4 Prosopagnosia:
//   Object chain: Φ_recognition(object) preserved (> AG_PHI_MIN).
//   Face chain: Φ_recognition(face) collapses (< object chain).
//   Dissociation between face and object recognition.
//
// T5 Determinism + modality specificity:
//   Two runs with identical seeds produce identical Φ values.
//   Modality specificity (Beauvois 1982): visual agnosia but tactile
//   recognition of the same object succeeds — same semantic store,
//   different sensory route proves the deficit is in visual mapping.
//
// ─── Stage0 hexa constraints honored ────────────────────────────
//   - plain `fn` only (no `pure fn` ≥3 float struct returns)
//   - `array` typed params only (no [float], no [str])
//   - No identifier-pattern match; sequential if-chains
//   - No `contains()` / `to_lower()` / `!(Effect)`
//   - No else-if in let-binding; flat mut + sequential if
//   - Single-line fn signatures / call sites / array literals
//   - No reserved keywords as variable names
//   - main() call at bottom
//   - AG_STEPS=24 (< 32)
//
// Law alignment:
//   Law 2   Observe never inject — Φ via MI measurement on traces
//   Law 4   Structure > feature — agnosia is STRUCTURAL chain break
//   Law 22  Feature addition → Φ down — 4 channels fixed, no surplus
//   Meta M8 Perception-to-recognition binding across levels
//
// Ref:
//   Lissauer 1890 | Farah 2004 Visual Agnosia | Milner 1991
//   Rubens & Benson 1971 | Bodamer 1947 | De Renzi 1986
//   Duchaine & Nakayama 2006 | Beauvois 1982 | Riddoch & Humphreys 1987

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Constants
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

let AG_STEPS          = 24            // timeline length (stage0 N<32)
let AG_BINS           = 6             // histogram bins for MI
let AG_EPS            = 0.0000000001

// Coupling strengths in normal recognition chain
let AG_COUPLE_STRONG  = 0.85          // normal coupling between stages
let AG_COUPLE_BROKEN  = 0.05          // agnosic pathway coupling

// Jitter amplitude per step
let AG_JITTER         = 0.04

// Gain parameters
let AG_GAIN_NORMAL    = 1.0           // healthy channel gain
let AG_GAIN_IMPAIRED  = 0.05          // agnosic channel gain

// Test gates
let AG_PHI_MIN        = 0.04          // baseline binding minimum per link
let AG_RECOG_MIN      = 0.0001        // product floor (3-way)
let AG_DROP_GAP       = 0.10          // detection threshold for Φ drop
let AG_PRESERVE_TOL   = 0.30          // preserved link drift tolerance
let AG_PROSO_GAP      = 0.03          // face vs object dissociation gap

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Math / PRNG primitives (L0-clean, no cross-engine import per AN7)
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn ag_abs(x: float) -> float {
    if x < 0.0 { return 0.0 - x }
    return x
}

fn ag_ln_safe(x: float) -> float {
    if x <= 0.0 { return 0.0 }
    return ln(x)
}

fn ag_min_f(a: float, b: float) -> float {
    if a < b { return a }
    return b
}

fn ag_max_f(a: float, b: float) -> float {
    if a > b { return a }
    return b
}

// Deterministic LCG — reproducibility (Law 2: observable, seed-stable)
fn ag_prng(seed: int) -> int {
    return (seed * 1103515245 + 12345) % 2147483648
}

fn ag_unit(seed: int) -> float {
    return to_float(seed % 1000000) / 1000000.0
}

fn ag_signed(seed: int) -> float {
    return ag_unit(seed) * 2.0 - 1.0
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Histogram MI (same recipe family — duplicated per AN7 L0-clean)
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn ag_bin_idx(x: float, lo: float, hi: float, nb: int) -> int {
    if hi <= lo { return 0 }
    let t = (x - lo) / (hi - lo)
    let mut idx = to_int(t * to_float(nb))
    if idx < 0 { idx = 0 }
    if idx >= nb { idx = nb - 1 }
    return idx
}

fn ag_counts(ids: array, nb: int) -> array {
    let n = len(ids)
    let mut c = []
    let mut k = 0
    while k < nb {
        let mut acc = 0.0
        let mut i = 0
        while i < n {
            if ids[i] == k { acc = acc + 1.0 }
            i = i + 1
        }
        c = c.push(acc)
        k = k + 1
    }
    return c
}

fn ag_entropy(v: array, lo: float, hi: float, nb: int) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut ids = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        ids = ids.push(ag_bin_idx(v[i], lo, hi, nb))
        i = i + 1
    }
    let cnt = ag_counts(ids, nb)
    let inv = 1.0 / to_float(n)
    let mut h = 0.0
    let mut k = 0
    while k < nb {
        let p = cnt[k] * inv
        if p > 0.0 { h = h - p * ag_ln_safe(p) }
        k = k + 1
    }
    return h
}

fn ag_joint_entropy(a: array, b: array, lo: float, hi: float, nb: int) -> float {
    let n = len(a)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut pair_ids = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        let ia = ag_bin_idx(a[i], lo, hi, nb)
        let ib = ag_bin_idx(b[i], lo, hi, nb)
        pair_ids = pair_ids.push(ia * nb + ib)
        i = i + 1
    }
    let cnt = ag_counts(pair_ids, nb * nb)
    let inv = 1.0 / to_float(n)
    let mut h = 0.0
    let mut k = 0
    while k < nb * nb {
        let p = cnt[k] * inv
        if p > 0.0 { h = h - p * ag_ln_safe(p) }
        k = k + 1
    }
    return h
}

fn ag_vec_min(v: array) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut m = v[0]
    let mut i = 1
    while i < n {
        if v[i] < m { m = v[i] }
        i = i + 1
    }
    return m
}

fn ag_vec_max(v: array) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut m = v[0]
    let mut i = 1
    while i < n {
        if v[i] > m { m = v[i] }
        i = i + 1
    }
    return m
}

fn ag_mi(a: array, b: array) -> float {
    let n = len(a)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    if len(b) != n { return 0.0 }
    let lo_a = ag_vec_min(a)
    let hi_a = ag_vec_max(a)
    let lo_b = ag_vec_min(b)
    let hi_b = ag_vec_max(b)
    let lo = ag_min_f(lo_a, lo_b)
    let hi = ag_max_f(hi_a, hi_b)
    let h_a = ag_entropy(a, lo, hi, AG_BINS)
    let h_b = ag_entropy(b, lo, hi, AG_BINS)
    let h_j = ag_joint_entropy(a, b, lo, hi, AG_BINS)
    let mi = h_a + h_b - h_j
    if mi < 0.0 { return 0.0 }
    return mi
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Recognition chain generation
//
// Normal recognition: sensory → percept → semantic → naming
// Each stage is driven by the previous stage with coupling + noise.
//
// The chain is causal:
//   sensory_t = structured signal (visual edges, orientation)
//   percept_t = gain_percept * coupling * sensory_t + noise
//   semantic_t = gain_semantic * coupling * percept_t + noise
//   naming_t = gain_naming * coupling * semantic_t + noise
//
// Agnosia is modeled by setting gain at the appropriate stage to
// AG_GAIN_IMPAIRED, which breaks the chain at that point and
// causes all downstream stages to decouple.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

// Generate sensory channel — independent structured driver.
// Represents raw visual features (edge orientations, spatial frequency).
fn ag_gen_sensory(seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut t = 0
    while t < AG_STEPS {
        s = ag_prng(s + t * 31)
        // Structured signal: triangular wave (edge activation pattern)
        let phase = to_float(t) / to_float(AG_STEPS)
        let mut tri = phase * 4.0 - 2.0
        if tri < 0.0 { tri = 0.0 - tri }
        let signal = 1.0 - tri
        let jit = AG_JITTER * ag_signed(s)
        out = out.push(signal + jit)
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Generate percept channel — bound shape representation from sensory input.
// gain_percept controls the quality of perceptual binding.
// Apperceptive agnosia: gain_percept → AG_GAIN_IMPAIRED.
fn ag_gen_percept(sensory: array, coupling: float, gain: float, seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut t = 0
    while t < AG_STEPS {
        s = ag_prng(s + t * 47)
        let driven = coupling * gain * sensory[t]
        let independent = (1.0 - coupling * gain) * ag_signed(s) * 0.3
        let jit = AG_JITTER * ag_signed(s + 5501)
        out = out.push(driven + independent + jit)
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Generate semantic channel — category/meaning activation from percept.
// gain_semantic controls meaning extraction.
// Associative agnosia: gain_semantic → AG_GAIN_IMPAIRED.
fn ag_gen_semantic(percept: array, coupling: float, gain: float, seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut t = 0
    while t < AG_STEPS {
        s = ag_prng(s + t * 61)
        let driven = coupling * gain * percept[t]
        let independent = (1.0 - coupling * gain) * ag_signed(s) * 0.3
        let jit = AG_JITTER * ag_signed(s + 7703)
        out = out.push(driven + independent + jit)
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Generate naming channel — lexical label activation from semantic.
// Naming depends on intact semantics; if semantic fails, naming fails.
fn ag_gen_naming(semantic: array, coupling: float, gain: float, seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut t = 0
    while t < AG_STEPS {
        s = ag_prng(s + t * 79)
        let driven = coupling * gain * semantic[t]
        let independent = (1.0 - coupling * gain) * ag_signed(s) * 0.3
        let jit = AG_JITTER * ag_signed(s + 9901)
        out = out.push(driven + independent + jit)
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Full recognition chain builder
//
// Parameters:
//   gain_percept  — perceptual binding quality (1.0 normal, 0.05 apperceptive)
//   gain_semantic — meaning extraction quality (1.0 normal, 0.05 associative)
//   gain_naming   — lexical access quality (always 1.0; fails downstream)
//   seed          — base seed for determinism
//
// Returns flat array of length 4 * AG_STEPS:
//   [0..AG_STEPS)             = sensory trace
//   [AG_STEPS..2*AG_STEPS)    = percept trace
//   [2*AG_STEPS..3*AG_STEPS)  = semantic trace
//   [3*AG_STEPS..4*AG_STEPS)  = naming trace
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn ag_build_chain(gain_percept: float, gain_semantic: float, gain_naming: float, seed: int) -> array {
    let sensory = ag_gen_sensory(seed)
    let percept = ag_gen_percept(sensory, AG_COUPLE_STRONG, gain_percept, seed + 1000)
    let semantic = ag_gen_semantic(percept, AG_COUPLE_STRONG, gain_semantic, seed + 2000)
    let naming = ag_gen_naming(semantic, AG_COUPLE_STRONG, gain_naming, seed + 3000)

    // Flatten into single array: sensory | percept | semantic | naming
    let mut flat = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < AG_STEPS {
        flat = flat.push(sensory[i])
        i = i + 1
    }
    let mut j = 0
    while j < AG_STEPS {
        flat = flat.push(percept[j])
        j = j + 1
    }
    let mut k = 0
    while k < AG_STEPS {
        flat = flat.push(semantic[k])
        k = k + 1
    }
    let mut m = 0
    while m < AG_STEPS {
        flat = flat.push(naming[m])
        m = m + 1
    }
    return flat
}

// Extract a channel trace from flat layout.
// channel: 0=sensory, 1=percept, 2=semantic, 3=naming
fn ag_extract_channel(flat: array, ch_idx: int) -> array {
    let offset = ch_idx * AG_STEPS
    let mut out = []
    let mut t = 0
    while t < AG_STEPS {
        out = out.push(flat[offset + t])
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Φ measurements for recognition chain
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

// Φ_percept = MI(sensory, percept) — perceptual binding strength
fn ag_phi_percept(flat: array) -> float {
    let sensory = ag_extract_channel(flat, 0)
    let percept = ag_extract_channel(flat, 1)
    return ag_mi(sensory, percept)
}

// Φ_semantic = MI(percept, semantic) — meaning extraction strength
fn ag_phi_semantic(flat: array) -> float {
    let percept = ag_extract_channel(flat, 1)
    let semantic = ag_extract_channel(flat, 2)
    return ag_mi(percept, semantic)
}

// Φ_naming = MI(semantic, naming) — lexical access strength
fn ag_phi_naming(flat: array) -> float {
    let semantic = ag_extract_channel(flat, 2)
    let naming = ag_extract_channel(flat, 3)
    return ag_mi(semantic, naming)
}

// Φ_recognition = product of chain links (any break collapses recognition)
fn ag_phi_recognition(flat: array) -> float {
    let p = ag_phi_percept(flat)
    let s = ag_phi_semantic(flat)
    let n = ag_phi_naming(flat)
    return p * s * n
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Prosopagnosia model — dual pathway (object LOC vs face FFA)
//
// Both pathways share the same chain architecture but with
// independent gains. Prosopagnosia selectively impairs the face
// pathway FFA while leaving the object pathway LOC intact.
//
// object_gain = 1.0 (LOC intact)
// face_gain   = AG_GAIN_IMPAIRED (FFA damaged)
//
// We build two full chains with different seeds (different objects
// activate different feature spaces) and compare their Φ_recognition.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn ag_build_object_chain(gain: float, seed: int) -> array {
    // Object chain through LOC pathway
    // All stages use the given gain for percept→semantic link;
    // percept formation itself is always intact for prosopagnosia
    return ag_build_chain(AG_GAIN_NORMAL, gain, AG_GAIN_NORMAL, seed)
}

fn ag_build_face_chain(gain: float, seed: int) -> array {
    // Face chain through FFA pathway
    // Face gain controls the specialized face→semantic binding
    return ag_build_chain(AG_GAIN_NORMAL, gain, AG_GAIN_NORMAL, seed)
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Modality specificity model — visual vs tactile input
//
// Same object, two sensory routes. Visual agnosia breaks the
// visual route but tactile recognition of the same object succeeds.
//
// We model this by generating two independent sensory channels
// (visual and tactile) that feed the same downstream chain structure.
// The visual pathway has impaired gain; the tactile pathway is intact.
//
// The key insight: SAME semantic/naming targets can be reached
// through an intact modality even when the visual route is broken.
// This proves the deficit is in the input mapping, not in the
// semantic store.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn ag_gen_tactile_sensory(seed: int) -> array {
    // Tactile input: different temporal structure than visual
    // (exploratory hand movements produce slower, smoother signals)
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut t = 0
    while t < AG_STEPS {
        s = ag_prng(s + t * 37)
        // Smoother signal: cosine-like exploration pattern
        let phase = to_float(t) / to_float(AG_STEPS) * 3.14159265
        // Taylor approximation: cos(x) ~ 1 - x^2/2 + x^4/24
        let mut y = phase
        while y > 3.14159265 { y = y - 6.28318530 }
        while y < 0.0 - 3.14159265 { y = y + 6.28318530 }
        let y2 = y * y
        let signal = 1.0 - 0.5 * y2 + 0.04166 * y2 * y2
        let jit = AG_JITTER * ag_signed(s)
        out = out.push(signal + jit)
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Build tactile recognition chain — same downstream structure, different input
fn ag_build_tactile_chain(gain_percept: float, gain_semantic: float, seed: int) -> array {
    let sensory = ag_gen_tactile_sensory(seed)
    let percept = ag_gen_percept(sensory, AG_COUPLE_STRONG, gain_percept, seed + 1000)
    let semantic = ag_gen_semantic(percept, AG_COUPLE_STRONG, gain_semantic, seed + 2000)
    let naming = ag_gen_naming(semantic, AG_COUPLE_STRONG, AG_GAIN_NORMAL, seed + 3000)

    let mut flat = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < AG_STEPS {
        flat = flat.push(sensory[i])
        i = i + 1
    }
    let mut j = 0
    while j < AG_STEPS {
        flat = flat.push(percept[j])
        j = j + 1
    }
    let mut k = 0
    while k < AG_STEPS {
        flat = flat.push(semantic[k])
        k = k + 1
    }
    let mut m = 0
    while m < AG_STEPS {
        flat = flat.push(naming[m])
        m = m + 1
    }
    return flat
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Self-tests T1..T5
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn check_T1() -> bool {
    // T1 Normal recognition — full chain operational.
    // Φ_percept, Φ_semantic, Φ_naming all > AG_PHI_MIN.
    // Φ_recognition (product) > AG_RECOG_MIN.
    let flat = ag_build_chain(AG_GAIN_NORMAL, AG_GAIN_NORMAL, AG_GAIN_NORMAL, 105001)

    let phi_p = ag_phi_percept(flat)
    let phi_s = ag_phi_semantic(flat)
    let phi_n = ag_phi_naming(flat)
    let phi_r = ag_phi_recognition(flat)
    println("  [T1] Phi_percept=" + str(phi_p) + " Phi_semantic=" + str(phi_s) + " Phi_naming=" + str(phi_n))
    println("  [T1] Phi_recognition(product)=" + str(phi_r))

    let mut ok = true
    if phi_p <= AG_PHI_MIN { ok = false }
    if phi_s <= AG_PHI_MIN { ok = false }
    if phi_n <= AG_PHI_MIN { ok = false }
    if phi_r <= AG_RECOG_MIN { ok = false }
    return ok
}

fn check_T2() -> bool {
    // T2 Apperceptive agnosia — percept formation fails, everything downstream collapses.
    // Φ_percept(apperceptive) << Φ_percept(normal)
    // Φ_semantic and Φ_naming also collapse because there is no coherent percept to process.

    // Normal baseline
    let flat_n = ag_build_chain(AG_GAIN_NORMAL, AG_GAIN_NORMAL, AG_GAIN_NORMAL, 105101)
    let phi_p_n = ag_phi_percept(flat_n)
    let phi_s_n = ag_phi_semantic(flat_n)
    let phi_r_n = ag_phi_recognition(flat_n)

    // Apperceptive: percept gain collapses
    let flat_a = ag_build_chain(AG_GAIN_IMPAIRED, AG_GAIN_NORMAL, AG_GAIN_NORMAL, 105101)
    let phi_p_a = ag_phi_percept(flat_a)
    let phi_s_a = ag_phi_semantic(flat_a)
    let phi_r_a = ag_phi_recognition(flat_a)

    let p_drop = phi_p_n - phi_p_a
    println("  [T2] Apperceptive: Phi_percept normal=" + str(phi_p_n) + " impaired=" + str(phi_p_a) + " drop=" + str(p_drop))
    println("  [T2] Phi_semantic normal=" + str(phi_s_n) + " impaired=" + str(phi_s_a))
    println("  [T2] Phi_recognition normal=" + str(phi_r_n) + " impaired=" + str(phi_r_a))

    let mut ok = true
    // Percept must drop substantially
    if p_drop <= AG_DROP_GAP { ok = false }
    // Downstream semantic should also degrade (percept is garbage, so semantic
    // gets random input — MI between random percept and driven semantic collapses)
    if phi_s_a >= phi_s_n { ok = false }
    // Overall recognition must be near-zero
    if phi_r_a >= phi_r_n { ok = false }
    return ok
}

fn check_T3() -> bool {
    // T3 Associative agnosia — percept preserved, semantic drops.
    // Patient can copy a drawing (Φ_percept intact) but cannot name what it is.

    // Normal baseline
    let flat_n = ag_build_chain(AG_GAIN_NORMAL, AG_GAIN_NORMAL, AG_GAIN_NORMAL, 105201)
    let phi_p_n = ag_phi_percept(flat_n)
    let phi_s_n = ag_phi_semantic(flat_n)

    // Associative: semantic gain collapses, percept preserved
    let flat_assoc = ag_build_chain(AG_GAIN_NORMAL, AG_GAIN_IMPAIRED, AG_GAIN_NORMAL, 105201)
    let phi_p_assoc = ag_phi_percept(flat_assoc)
    let phi_s_assoc = ag_phi_semantic(flat_assoc)

    let p_drift = ag_abs(phi_p_n - phi_p_assoc)
    let s_drop = phi_s_n - phi_s_assoc
    println("  [T3] Associative: Phi_percept normal=" + str(phi_p_n) + " assoc=" + str(phi_p_assoc) + " drift=" + str(p_drift))
    println("  [T3] Phi_semantic normal=" + str(phi_s_n) + " assoc=" + str(phi_s_assoc) + " drop=" + str(s_drop))

    let mut ok = true
    // Percept must be preserved (patient can copy drawings)
    if p_drift > AG_PRESERVE_TOL { ok = false }
    // Semantic must drop substantially (cannot assign meaning)
    if s_drop <= AG_DROP_GAP { ok = false }
    return ok
}

fn check_T4() -> bool {
    // T4 Prosopagnosia — face recognition impaired, object recognition intact.
    // Bodamer 1947 / Duchaine & Nakayama 2006: FFA damage selectively impairs
    // face recognition while LOC-mediated object recognition is preserved.

    // Object pathway: LOC intact (gain = 1.0 for semantic link)
    let obj_flat = ag_build_object_chain(AG_GAIN_NORMAL, 105301)
    let phi_obj = ag_phi_recognition(obj_flat)
    let phi_obj_s = ag_phi_semantic(obj_flat)

    // Face pathway: FFA impaired (gain = AG_GAIN_IMPAIRED for semantic link)
    let face_flat = ag_build_face_chain(AG_GAIN_IMPAIRED, 105401)
    let phi_face = ag_phi_recognition(face_flat)
    let phi_face_s = ag_phi_semantic(face_flat)

    let dissoc = phi_obj - phi_face
    println("  [T4] Prosopagnosia: Phi_recognition object=" + str(phi_obj) + " face=" + str(phi_face))
    println("  [T4] Phi_semantic object=" + str(phi_obj_s) + " face=" + str(phi_face_s))
    println("  [T4] dissociation (object - face)=" + str(dissoc))

    let mut ok = true
    // Object recognition must be positive and functional
    if phi_obj <= AG_RECOG_MIN { ok = false }
    // Object semantic link preserved
    if phi_obj_s <= AG_PHI_MIN { ok = false }
    // Face recognition must be impaired relative to object
    if phi_face >= phi_obj { ok = false }
    // Dissociation gap must be detectable
    if dissoc <= AG_PROSO_GAP { ok = false }
    return ok
}

fn check_T5() -> bool {
    // T5 Determinism + latency.
    // Two runs with identical seeds must produce identical Φ values (Law 2).
    // Root cause: deterministic LCG seeds guarantee reproducibility.
    // Also verifies modality specificity: visual agnosia but tactile intact.
    // Beauvois 1982: same object, different pathway — visual fails, touch works.

    // --- Part A: Determinism ---
    // Run 1
    let flat_1 = ag_build_chain(AG_GAIN_NORMAL, AG_GAIN_NORMAL, AG_GAIN_NORMAL, 105501)
    let phi_r_1 = ag_phi_recognition(flat_1)
    let phi_p_1 = ag_phi_percept(flat_1)

    // Run 2 (identical seeds)
    let flat_2 = ag_build_chain(AG_GAIN_NORMAL, AG_GAIN_NORMAL, AG_GAIN_NORMAL, 105501)
    let phi_r_2 = ag_phi_recognition(flat_2)
    let phi_p_2 = ag_phi_percept(flat_2)

    let delta_r = ag_abs(phi_r_1 - phi_r_2)
    let delta_p = ag_abs(phi_p_1 - phi_p_2)

    println("  [T5] Determinism: Phi_recognition run1=" + str(phi_r_1) + " run2=" + str(phi_r_2) + " delta=" + str(delta_r))
    println("  [T5] Determinism: Phi_percept run1=" + str(phi_p_1) + " run2=" + str(phi_p_2) + " delta=" + str(delta_p))

    // --- Part B: Modality specificity (Beauvois 1982) ---
    // Visual pathway impaired: cannot recognize object by sight
    let vis_flat = ag_build_chain(AG_GAIN_IMPAIRED, AG_GAIN_NORMAL, AG_GAIN_NORMAL, 105601)
    let phi_vis = ag_phi_recognition(vis_flat)

    // Tactile pathway intact: same object recognized by touch
    let tact_flat = ag_build_tactile_chain(AG_GAIN_NORMAL, AG_GAIN_NORMAL, 105701)
    let phi_tact = ag_phi_recognition(tact_flat)

    let modality_gap = phi_tact - phi_vis
    println("  [T5] Modality: Phi_visual(impaired)=" + str(phi_vis) + " Phi_tactile(intact)=" + str(phi_tact))
    println("  [T5] Modality gap (tactile - visual)=" + str(modality_gap))

    let mut ok = true
    // Determinism: identical seeds must produce identical results
    if delta_r > AG_EPS { ok = false }
    if delta_p > AG_EPS { ok = false }
    // Modality specificity: tactile recognition must exceed impaired visual
    if phi_tact <= AG_RECOG_MIN { ok = false }
    if modality_gap <= 0.0 { ok = false }
    return ok
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Main — execute 5 self-tests
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn main() {
    println("[agnosia_phi] P105 — Agnosia Phi (perception without recognition)")
    println("  steps=" + str(AG_STEPS) + " bins=" + str(AG_BINS))
    println("  chain: sensory -> percept -> semantic -> naming")
    println("  refs: Lissauer 1890 | Farah 2004 | Milner 1991 | Bodamer 1947 | Duchaine 2006")
    println("")

    let t1 = check_T1()
    if t1 { println("T1 PASS — normal recognition (percept+semantic+naming all > floor)") } else { println("T1 FAIL") }

    let t2 = check_T2()
    if t2 { println("T2 PASS — apperceptive agnosia (Phi_percept drops, downstream collapses)") } else { println("T2 FAIL") }

    let t3 = check_T3()
    if t3 { println("T3 PASS — associative agnosia (Phi_percept preserved, Phi_semantic drops)") } else { println("T3 FAIL") }

    let t4 = check_T4()
    if t4 { println("T4 PASS — prosopagnosia (face Phi drops, object Phi preserved)") } else { println("T4 FAIL") }

    let t5 = check_T5()
    if t5 { println("T5 PASS — determinism + modality specificity (visual agnosia, tactile intact)") } else { println("T5 FAIL") }

    println("")

    // Root cause comment: stage0 long && chains may mishandle short-circuit
    // ordering — use a mutable bool accumulator with sequential guards
    // (same idiom as depersonalization_phi / body_swap_phi).
    let mut pass_count = 0
    if t1 { pass_count = pass_count + 1 }
    if t2 { pass_count = pass_count + 1 }
    if t3 { pass_count = pass_count + 1 }
    if t4 { pass_count = pass_count + 1 }
    if t5 { pass_count = pass_count + 1 }

    let mut all = true
    if !t1 { all = false }
    if !t2 { all = false }
    if !t3 { all = false }
    if !t4 { all = false }
    if !t5 { all = false }

    if all {
        println("[agnosia_phi] 5/5 PASS — P105 DONE")
    } else {
        println("[agnosia_phi] " + str(pass_count) + "/5 PASS — SOME FAILED")
    }
}

main()
